  "text": "where sgn( ⋅ ) is sign function, f s is the sub-carrier frequency, and φ is the phase of subcarrier. Two common values of φ are 0 or π /2, for which the resultant BOC signals are referred to as sine-phased BOC or cosine-phased BOC, respectively. In this Chapter, we focus on sine-phased case. For information on cosine-phased BOC signal unambiguous processing, see [CITATION_1] . Using the terminology from [CITATION_2] ), a sine phased BOC modulated signal is denoted as BOC s (m,n), where m means the ratio of the square wave frequency f s to 1.023 MHz, and n represents the ratio of the spreading code rate f c to 1.023 MHz. m and n are constrained to positive integer mn ≥ , and the ratio M = 2m/n is referred to as BOC-modulation order, which is constrained to positive integer.",
